Musa acuminata

   [7848.jpg]
    Authority   Colla
      Family    Liliopsida:Zingiberidae:Zingiberales:Musaceae
     Synonyms
   Common names
      Editor
   Ecocrop code 7848

   Notes
   BRIEF DESCRIPTION A herbaceous plant with a fleshy, watery stem made up
   of large, spirally arranged, overlapping leaf bases called sheaths. The
   plant stands erect, 1.5-6 m tall and the stem has a diameter of up to
   30 cm at the base. Leaves are 1-2 m long and up to 60 cm wide. The
   inflorescence is horizontal or pendulous. Fruits may be 10-25 cm long,
   green, yellow or brown, cylindric or angled, and seeded or seedless.
   USES It is mainly grown for its edible fruits. The ripe fruit is eaten
   fresh, baked, fried, or roasted and is made into a type of vinegar, and
   it also have medicinal properties. Young stalks and leaves are fed to
   livestock and leaves are used for wrapping foods, for cooking and as
   plates. The underground stem can be eaten as a vegetable. KILLING T
   Depending on the cultivar banana may be killed by frost and damage when
   the temperature falls below 7-12Â°C for more than 12 hours or it may
   withstand

